			<section id='inspiration'>
				<div class="medium-8 medium-centered columns">
					<h1>From Inspiration to Metaphor</h1>
					<p>We started with question "how might we teach kids about complex emotions?" Our initial inspirations came from Inside Out's emotional overlaps and Shrek's metaphor of "[ogres] are like onions, we have to peel them back one layer at a time." In considering interactions that would teach both these concepts, we came to Russian nesting dolls as the most compelling metaphor. Its affordances enables teaching how our emotions have layers and that these layers might be represented differently.</p>
				</div>

				<figure class="large-12 columns">
					<img src="images/emoshkas/inspo.png">
					<figcaption>We started with existing mental models of emotions as explained by figures children are familiar with, such as Inside Out and Shrek. When we tried to mix the two, we ended up with the metaphor of stacking dolls.</figcaption>
				</figure>

				<div class="clearfix"></div>


			</section>


			<section id='context'>
				<div class="medium-8 medium-centered columns">
					<h1>Defining Context</h1>
					<p>We started by conducting an <a href="/assets/Emoshkas-BBAFinalProjectPacket.pdf">academic literature review</a> and <a href="/assets/Emoshkas-BBAFinalProjectPacket.pdf">existing products roundup</a>. Theories on social understanding explain that by early elementary school, children begin to identify emotions in themselves. Research also suggests that talking aloud through scenarios and taking on different perspectives teach children to solve problems through talking, not punching. We sketched a <a href="images/emoshkas/setup.png">few</a> <a href="images/emoshkas/playv1.jpg">different</a> <a href="images/emoshkas/playv2.jpg">storyboards</a>, to simulate play. Understanding where our product might fit in, we narrowed our context. </p>
				</div>

